ershire, England, United Kingdom","Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"–":"Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1235–1299":"1235–1299","1290–1386":"1290–1386","–Female":"Overleden","1235":"1235","1299":"1299","1386":"1386","ABT 1290":"circa 1290","1290":"1290","Defford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Defford, Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1235–1299":"1235–1299","1290–1386":"1290–1386","–Female":"Deceased","1235":"1235","1299":"1299","1386":"1386","ABT 1290":"about 1290","1290":"1290","Defford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Defford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Despencer was born as the son of Sir John Le Despencer and Anne. He had at least 1 son with Anne de Lou. He died in Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1235–1299":"1235–1299","1290–1386":"1290–1386","–Female":"Surnud","1235":"1235","1299":"1299","1386":"1386","ABT 1290":"umbes 1290","1290":"1290","Defford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Defford, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1235–1299":"1235–1299","1290–1386":"1290–1386","–Female":"Kuollut","1235":"1235","1299":"1299","1386":"1386","ABT 1290":"noin 1290","1290":"1290","Defford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Defford, Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1235–1299":"1235–1299","1290–1386":"1290–1